SIMPLE: slabber
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slabber
<hw>Slab"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slabbered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Slabbering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>slaberen</ets>; akin to LG. & D. <ets>slabbern</ets>, G.
<ets>schlabbern</ets>, LG. & D. <ets>slabben</ets>, G.
<ets>schlabben</ets>, Icel. <ets>slafra</ets>. Cf. <er>Slaver</er>,
<er>Slobber</er>, <er>Slubber</er>.]</ety> <def>To let saliva or some
liquid fall from the mouth carelessly, like a child or an idiot; to
drivel; to drool.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>slaver</asp>, and
<asp>slobber</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slabber</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slabber
<hw>Slab"ber</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wet and foul
spittle, or as if with spittle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>slabbered</qex> me over, from cheek to cheek, with his
great tongue.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spill liquid upon; to smear carelessly; to spill,
as liquid food or drink, in careless eating or drinking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The milk pan and cream pot so <qex>slabbered</qex> and tost⟦br⟧
That butter is wanting and cheese is half lost.</q>
<rj><qau>Tusser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slabber</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slabber
<hw>Slab"ber</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Spittle; saliva; slaver.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slabber</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Slabber
<hw>Slab"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 1st
<er>Slab</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A saw for
cutting slabs from logs.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A slabbing
machine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slabberer</ent>⟦br⟧
